some of the most current research on Asian American religions from a social science perspective. The volume focuses on religion in Asian American communities in New York, Houston, Los Angeles, and the Silicon Valley/Bay Area, and it includes a current demographic overview of the various Asian populations across the United States. It also provides information on current trends, such as that Filipino and Korean Americans are the most religiously observant people in America, that over 60 percent of Asian Americans who have a religious identification are Christian, and that one-third of Muslims in the United States are Asian Americans. Rather than organizing the book around particular ethnic groups or religions, Asian American Religions centers on thematic issues, like symbols and rituals, political boundaries, and generation gaps, in order to highlight the role of Asian American religions in negotiating, accepting, redefining, changing, and creating boundaries in the communities' social life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAsian AmericansxReligion. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aBender, Courtney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarnes, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarnes, Tony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGonzalez, Joaquin L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuest, Kenneth J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeung, Russell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Rebecca Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlineberg, Stephen L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurien, Prema A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/